    • getEditNode

      public javafx.scene.Node getEditNode()
      Creates an editing node, or the User Interface that is used to edit the item's effect

      This node consists of 3 boxes, with labels above each one. There is a text field for the Value, Bonus Type, and Attribute.

      • Value - The value of the effect. The user can input either a single number, or specify a range of numbers, such as typing "1-4" for a range of 1-4.
      • Bonus Type - The stacking / bonus type of the effect. This specifies what type of bonus the effect has, such that multiple values of the same bonus type to the same effect do not stack
      • Attribute - The Attribute that the effect gives a bonus to. Separating multiple effects by commas will present a multi-selector, giving multiple options on the display node .

      Changing values in here will not automatically update any current instances of getDisplayNode()

      Returns:
      GridPane with the specified Text Fields and their labels above
      Since:
      2.0.0
      See Also:
      getDisplayNode()

    • getDisplayNode

      public javafx.scene.Node getDisplayNode()
      Creates a display node for the effect, or the User Interface to display for the effect in the gear-set layout

      This displays the value, bonus type, and specified attribute in a single line

      • Value - The value will display as a single number (in a Text object), if a single number is specified. Otherwise, if the effect specifies a range, it will display a Spinner with the minimum and maximum values as the specified minimum and maximum values
      • Bonus Type - Will always be a Text object with the bonus type.
      • Attribute - If only one attribute is specified, will combine with the Bonus Type's Text as the given Attribute. If multiple attributes are specified, this will display a ComboBox of all the given options, updating the effect whenever the user selects an option
      Returns:
      An HBox with UI elements representing the effect
      Since:
      2.0.0
      See Also:
      getEditNode()

    • setAttributes

      public void setAttributes​(java.lang.String input)
      Sets the attributes from a user-inputted string.
      • If only a single attribute is given, will set the attribute array to an array with length = 1, the first value being the specified attribute
      • If multiple attributes are given, this will separate the attributes (separated by commas) into the array.
      Then this will verify that the set index is within the range of the items, defaulting to index = 0.
      Parameters:
      input - User string input
      Since:
      2.0.1
      See Also:
      getEditNode()

    • setAttributeIndex

      public void setAttributeIndex​(int attributeIndex)
      Sets the attribute's current index.

      This function is typically called by the getDisplayNode() method, if there are multiple attributes specified

      Parameters:
      attributeIndex - The index of the attribute. Checks whether or not the index given is within the attribute array's range. If it is out of bounds, the stored attribute index will be unchanged.
      Since:
      2.0.1
      See Also:
      getDisplayNode()

      public void setValue​(double value)

      This will clamp the value between the Minimum and the Maximum if the effect has a specified range.

      Parameters:
      value - Effect value to set to the item.
      Since:

    • setValue

      public void setValue​(java.lang.String input)
      Sets the value of the effect.

      This will take a user-input and set the Value, Maximum, and Minimum depending on the input

      • If the user specifies a single number, the Value, Maximum, and Minimum will all be set to that number
      • If the user specifies a range ("4-7"), this will set the Minimum and Maximum values accordingly, and the Value will be set to the Maximum
      Parameters:
      input - User-Input String for the effect's Value, specifically from the getEditNode()
      Since:
      2.0.1
      See Also:
      getEditNode()

    • setValueOverride

      public void setValueOverride​(double value)
      Sets the value of the effect.

      If the Value is out of the range specified by the Maximum and Minimum, it will extend the range to include the given value

      Parameters:
      value - Effect Value to set to the item.
      Since:
      2.0.1
